SQL stands for Structured Query Language â€” a special language used to talk to databases. 
With SQL you can create, read, update, or delete data stored in tables (database operations). 

In short: SQL lets you manage and retrieve data from databases in a structured and standardized way. 
ğŸ”¹ Why SQL is Important / When We Use It
    Databases widely used in applications (websites, apps, business systems) store data in tables.
    SQL gives a consistent way to ask questions or get data: e.g. â€œGive me all users who signed up after Jan 2025â€, or â€œWhat are all orders above â‚¹1000?â€, etc.
    Because SQL is standard and widely supported, learning SQL helps you work with almost any relational database (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.).
ğŸ”¹ SQL: Data-centric â€” not code-centric
    Unlike general-purpose programming languages (Java, Python), SQL is declarative: you specify what you want (e.g. â€œselect these rows where condition Xâ€), not necessarily how to fetch them. This makes it simpler for data tasks.
ğŸ”¹ Typical Things You Do with SQL
  Create a new database / table.
  Insert data (rows) into a table.
  Query data (read): get specific rows/columns.
  Update data (change existing data).
  Delete data (remove rows).
  These operations make SQL a full toolkit for database data management.
